Diseases of Globalization
Globalization is being tested as severely as never before.
Everywhere, its tensions rumble.
The great majority of Black Africa, South America, the Middle East, and Central Asia stagnate or struggle within economic decline.
North America, Western Europe, and Japan are mired in slow growth and risk another recession.
The war now threatens in Iraq.
For supporters of open markets and free trade, this situation presents major challenges.
Why is globalization so threatened?
Why are its benefits apparently concentrated in only a few places?
Can a more balanced globalization be implemented?
There is no simple answer to these questions.
Open markets are necessary for economic growth, but they are hardly sufficient.
Some regions of the world have gained significant benefits from globalization, particularly East Asia and China in recent years.
Some regions have, however, gained only meager benefits, especially Sub-Saharan Africa.
The U.S. government claims that poor countries are responsible for the majority of the problems they face.
The slow growth of Africa, assert American leaders, is caused by the incompetence of the African government.
However, life is more complicated than the Bush administration believes.
Consider the best-governed countries in Africa: Ghana, Tanzania, Malawi, and The Gambia.
Each of them has experienced a decline in living standards over the past two decades, while a large number of Asian countries that were ranked among the last in international comparisons on the governance of each country (Pakistan, Bangladesh, Myanmar, and Sri Lanka) have experienced better economic growth.
It is true that economic performance is determined not only by governance standards, but also by geopolitics, geography, and economic structure.
Countries with large populations and therefore large internal markets tend to grow more rapidly than countries with small populations.
(As with all economic trends of this kind, there are exceptions).
Coastal countries tend to be more successful than landlocked countries.
Countries with high levels of malaria tend to experience slower growth than countries with lower levels of malaria.
Developing countries bordering rich markets, such as Mexico, tend to be more successful than countries located far from the main markets.
These differences are of great importance.
If rich countries do not care much about these structural issues, the gap between the winners and the losers will continue to widen.
If rich countries blame the unlucky countries for the responsibility, claiming that they are in some way culturally or politically unsuitable to benefit from globalization, we will not only create deeper pockets of poverty but also intensify the unrest.
This, in turn, will lead to increased levels of violence, hostile reactions, and terrorism.
It is therefore time to adopt a more serious approach to globalization than what rich countries, and particularly the United States, offer.
This approach must begin with the most urgent task, namely meeting the basic needs of the poorest people in the world.
In some cases, their suffering can be alleviated mainly through better governance within their own country.
But in others, an honest look at the evidence gathered will reveal that the main causes of poverty relate to disease, climate instability, poor soils, market distances, etc.
An honest assessment would further indicate that the poorest countries are unable to gather sufficient funds to resolve such problems on their own.
Rather than seeing rich countries give more lessons on the bad governance of poor countries, real solutions require that rich countries provide sufficient financial assistance to overcome the most entrenched barriers.
An example will strikingly illustrate this situation.
Controlling diseases requires a health system capable of providing survival medications and basic preventive services such as bed nets to fight malaria and vitamins to combat nutritional deficiencies.
This system costs at least about 40 dollars per person per year.
This amount is just a grain of sand for rich countries that systematically spend over 2,000 dollars per person per year on health, but it exceeds the means of poor countries like Malawi, which have annual incomes of only 200 dollars per person.
A functioning health system would cost more than the entire income of its government!
Even if Malawi is well-governed, its population will die in large numbers from diseases as long as it does not receive adequate assistance.
The success of globalization requires that we think more like doctors and less like preachers.
Instead of blaming the poor for their "sins," we must offer careful diagnoses, as any good doctor would, for each country and region, in order to understand the fundamental factors that are slowing their economic growth and development.
In some regions such as the Andes and Central Asia, the problem mainly stems from geographical isolation.
There, the task is to build roads, air links, and internet connectivity to help these remote regions establish productive links with the world.
Wealthy countries must contribute to the financing of these projects.
In Sub-Saharan Africa, the main challenges concern disease control, soil fertility, and the development of educational opportunities.
Once again, more foreign assistance is required.
In other regions, the main problems concern a lack of water, discrimination against women or other groups, or a variety of specific problems.
It is now time to take the complexities inherent in globalization seriously.
The ideology of a one-size-fits-all approach from Washington's consensus is outdated.
On the eve of war, it is urgent to tackle the tough task of ensuring that everyone benefits from globalization.
We can achieve this if we remove the ideological blinders of the rich and if we mobilize a partnership between the rich and the poor.
Our shared future depends on it.
